## Attribution Models

| Model | How It Works | Strengths | Limitations |
|-------|-------------|-----------|------------|
| Last-touch | Credits the final social interaction before conversion | Simple, easy to implement | Ignores awareness and consideration touchpoints |
| First-touch | Credits the first social interaction | Values discovery and top-of-funnel | Ignores nurturing and decision-stage content |
| Linear | Equal credit to all social touchpoints | Acknowledges full journey | Over-credits low-impact touches |
| Time-decay | More credit to interactions closer to conversion | Balances journey and recency | Complex to set up |
| Incrementality | Measures lift from social vs. holdout group | Most accurate for proving true impact | Requires scale and testing infrastructure |

## Common Pitfalls

### Reporting Without Insight

Wrong: Send a weekly report that lists numbers (impressions: 50K, engagement rate: 3.2%, followers: +127) with no context, comparison, or recommendation.

Right: Every metric should answer "so what?" Compare to targets, previous periods, and benchmarks. End every report section with a recommended action based on the data.

### Optimizing for the Wrong Metric

Wrong: Optimize all content for maximum reach (impressions) when the business goal is lead generation. Celebrate going viral on a post that drove zero clicks.

Right: Align content optimization with the metric that maps to your business objective. If the goal is leads, optimize for click-through rate and conversion rate, not impressions.

### Ignoring Qualitative Data

Wrong: Make all decisions based on quantitative metrics while ignoring what people are actually saying in comments, DMs, and mentions.

Right: Quantitative data tells you what is happening. Qualitative data (comment themes, DM questions, sentiment) tells you why. Read comments. Read DMs. Let audience language inform content strategy.
